# Releasing Cozip.jl

A short guide for releasing a new version. Follow the steps in order. The Julia binding has more moving parts than the others, but it's mechanical once you know it.

## The five steps

### 1. Bump the version

Edit `VERSION` at the repo root. Bump at least one of the four CalVer parts.

```
2026.5.16
```

### 2. Commit and tag

```bash
git add VERSION
git commit -m "release 2026.5.16"
git tag v2026.5.16
git push origin main --tags
```

The tag is what triggers the release workflow.

### 3. Wait for the workflow

The workflow has to finish before you register the package. The job to watch is `regenerate-artifacts-toml`. It adds a follow-up commit to main with the new `julia/Artifacts.toml`, and you need that commit before step 5.

The pipeline takes around ten minutes. Make tea.

Watch it from the Actions tab on GitHub. When `regenerate-artifacts-toml` goes green, move on.

### 4. Pull the bot commit

```bash
git pull origin main
```

This pulls down the commit the workflow just pushed. The message looks like `chore(julia): regenerate Artifacts.toml for v2026.5.16`.

Skip this and step 5 will register a version that downloads outdated binaries. It won't error, it'll just be wrong. Pull.

### 5. Register in AsteriskRegistry

Run this from the repo root.

```bash
julia -e 'using Pkg; Pkg.Registry.update("AsteriskRegistry"); using LocalRegistry; register("./julia"; registry="AsteriskRegistry", push=true)'
```

This takes the tree hash of `julia/` at the current commit (the one you just pulled), adds the entry to AsteriskRegistry, and pushes.

Done.

## Verifying the release

Try this in a fresh Julia session.

```julia
using Pkg
Pkg.activate(; temp=true)
Pkg.Registry.add(Pkg.RegistrySpec(url="https://github.com/asterisk-labs/AsteriskRegistry"))
Pkg.add("Cozip")
using Cozip
Cozip.LibCozip.cozip_version()
```

The version it prints should match the `VERSION` file. If it doesn't, the package is loading binaries from an older release. The usual cause is that you skipped step 4.

## Common errors

### `ERROR: Unknown package julia`

You wrote `register("julia"; ...)` instead of `register("./julia"; ...)`. LocalRegistry sees a plain string and looks for a package called "julia". Adding `./` makes it a path.

### `ERROR: no path or url specified for registry`

On Julia 1.12 and up, `Pkg.Registry.add` doesn't take URLs as plain strings anymore. Wrap the URL in a `RegistrySpec`, or hit `]` to enter package mode where URLs work directly.

### `! [rejected] main -> main (fetch first)`

Someone pushed to AsteriskRegistry between your local pull and your push. LocalRegistry resets your local clone for you, so nothing is broken. Just retry.

### `Pkg.add("Cozip")` says nothing changed

AsteriskRegistry isn't loaded in this depot. Add it first with `Pkg.Registry.add(Pkg.RegistrySpec(url="..."))`, then retry.

## Why the order matters

The tag points at the commit where you bumped `VERSION`. The workflow then adds one more commit on top, with the new `Artifacts.toml`. LocalRegistry reads whatever is in your working directory right now. If you register before pulling, you save a tree hash for a directory that still has the old `Artifacts.toml`.

No error. The user just gets a package that downloads old binaries. The worst kind of bug, because it works.

Pull before you register.